The performance considerations for disk storage (IOPS and throughput) are independent of the programming language you use, as they are more related to how data is read from and written to the disk and the computational demands of your tasks.

Why This Still Applies:
Data Manipulation: Whether in R or Python, manipulating a dataset of 2 million rows and 100 columns (approximately 2GB) involves similar I/O operations, and the SSD’s performance will affect how quickly data can be read into memory and written back to disk.

XGBoost and Computational Tasks: Training machine learning models and performing hyper-parameter tuning are computationally intensive tasks that rely heavily on both CPU/GPU resources and the underlying disk’s speed for reading data and writing temporary files. This is true regardless of whether you’re using R or Python.

Multi-User Environment: When multiple users are working on a shared virtual server, the combined disk I/O from different users' R processes can add up, making a faster SSD (like Premium SSD) beneficial to avoid slowdowns.

Summary:
RStudio and R-based Workloads: The recommendations for Standard vs. Premium SSD apply equally to R, as they would to Python, because the underlying factors (data size, computational intensity, multi-user environment) are the same.
Premium SSD remains the recommended choice if you anticipate heavy computational tasks or multiple users working simultaneously. If your workloads are typically lighter, Standard SSD could suffice, but be prepared to upgrade if performance issues arise.
